aux, Dante, Boccaccio and the heroes of Old French narrative, no more or less than their modern lyric counterparts, come to light in new and newly complicated ways.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChristianity and literature. 0aHuman body in literature. 0aLiterature, MedievalxHistory and criticism. 0aLiterature, MedievalxStudy and teaching. 0aLiterature, MedievalxTheory, etc. 0aMedievalismxHistoryy19th century. 0aPoetry, ModernxHistory and criticism. 0aPoetry. 0aSpiritualism in literature. 0aTransfiguration (Spiritualism) in literature. 4aLiterature Studies 2020. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aAttention.  aEmbodiment.  aEroticism.  aLyric.  aMedievalism.  aMiddle Ages.  aMonasticism.  aPoetry.  aTheology.  aTransfiguration.1 aHowie, Cary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2021 eBook-Packagez978311128198840uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152614866740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526148667423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526148667/original  a978-3-11-128198-8  Manchester University Press 2021 eBook-Packageb2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles